PHP has had type hints for classes for more than a decade now:<p><pre><code>  function foobar(MyClass $foo) {
     // do stuff
  }
  foobar(new NotMyClass()); // throws an error
</code></pre>
This just adds type hints for the scalar types (integer, float, string and boolean).<p>Since PHP has a long tradition of weak typing and this is what PHP&#x27;s built-in and extension functions use, weak is the default behaviour, allowing some conversions:<p><pre><code>  function foo(int $x) {
     var_dump($x);
  }
  foo(&quot;12&quot;); // produces int(12)
  foo(null); // throws an error
</code></pre>
But, you can optionally turn on a strict type-checking mode for scalars on a per-file basis, which doesn&#x27;t allow conversions:<p><pre><code>  <?php
  declare(strict_types=1);

  function foo(int $x) {
     var_dump($x);
  }
  foo(&quot;12&quot;); // throws an error
  foo(null); // throws an error</code></pre>
